Bryan Gin-ge Chen (Jun 04 2020 at 07:31):

Here's a script I'm currently running for step 2. Save this as profile.sh somewhere (and change gtime to /usr/bin/time if you're running linux). Run it from mathlib's src/ directory:

#!/usr/bin/env bash

if [[ $# = 2 ]]; then
  dir="$1"
  out="$2"
else
  dir="."
  out="profile_output.json"
fi

echo "{" > $out
for filename in $(find $dir -name '*.lean'); do
  [ -e "$filename" ] || continue
  echo $filename
  # gtime is homebrew's gnu-time; replace with /usr/bin/time on linux
  gtime -a -o $out -f"\"$filename\":[%U,%S,%e]," lean -j1 $filename
done
# strip comma from last line
sed -i '' '$ s/.$//' $out
echo "}" >> $out

By default the output is generated in a file profile_output.json which looks like this:

{
"./tactic/generalize_proofs.lean":[0.52,0.12,0.75],
"./tactic/elide.lean":[0.62,0.10,0.74],
"./tactic/split_ifs.lean":[0.74,0.10,0.86],
"./tactic/norm_cast.lean":[1.86,0.11,1.98],

The three numbers are user time, sys time, and elapsed time, measured in seconds. The max precision seems to be hundredths of a second, but the variance seems to be much higher.

Mario Carneiro (Jun 15 2020 at 07:22):

Oh, I finally understood what the alternative is with your "Don't use get_param" advice

Mario Carneiro (Jun 15 2020 at 07:23):

Indeed, I think we can abstract this a bit and deserialize more complicated things through has_reflect

Gabriel Ebner (Jun 15 2020 at 07:26):

I'm not sure how easy it is to deserialize the result of has_reflect name though (because it constructs the name out of strings). The hack serialization scheme maps a name n to the constant n, which is obviously easy and fast to deserialize. I don't know if we have a good way to deserialize strings.

Mario Carneiro (Jun 15 2020 at 07:36):

That's true, ad hoc serialization will perform better in this case, especially since name is literally a component of expr. But a generic has_reflect approach will work with other kinds of structured data without requiring any on the spot compilation, because the reflection routine is prepared beforehand.

Mario Carneiro (Jun 15 2020 at 07:39):

actually has_reflect is the wrong class. Here the typeclass should have type expr -> tactic A instead of A -> expr

Mario Carneiro (Jun 15 2020 at 07:39):

or maybe expr -> A

Scott Morrison (Oct 13 2022 at 08:36):

Didn't someone do a power-law fit for LOC and compile time? I remember it being somewhere between 2 and 3.

That's pretty reasonable: any tactic like simp that has to do something linear in the library size ensures that the exponent is at least 2.

Alex J. Best (Oct 13 2022 at 15:37):

This is really starting to make me question whether bare simp's are the right format to keep proofs in a mathlib like repo, and whether we should simp only everything by default, even finishing proofs.
A very rough count makes me believe that simp is used as often as an intermediate step than as a finishing tactic, so it will only get twice as annoying to do refactors involving renaming, would this be worth it if everyones branches built on average 30 mins faster? Or 1 hour or 2?
I'd like to gather some data on the effects of making such a change, provided I can find a good way to automate the process.
Of course there is also the ugliness factor of replacing nice one line proofs when defining structures with a 3 line simp block, but is the aesthetics worth the stress on CI?

Eric Rodriguez (Oct 13 2022 at 16:21):

I suggested in the past that we could have files that kept the simp only output cached in the background; for this, we'd definitely need a more reliable squeeze_simp, but I still think it's a good idea for speed unless lean4 is literally here in <1month or so. Last I looked at it, squeeze_simp is mostly reliable, there's still issues with expressions that provide extra values (so for example if you squeeze_simp with a term like my_lemma _ _ h.a it will be awful) but otherwise solid enough

Alex J. Best (Oct 13 2022 at 17:14):

Scott Morrison (Oct 13 2022 at 23:39):

re: caching, there's also the question of doing in Lean 3 (hard and/or messy) or in Lean 4 (hopefully lots more options!). If we had on the horizon a plan for tactics being able to cache data between runs in Lean 4, and anticipated this making a big difference for simp in mathlib4, there wouldn't be much point squeezing lots of mathlib3 simps.

Gabriel Ebner (Oct 13 2022 at 23:50):

a plan for tactics being able to cache data between runs in Lean 4

If you mean reusing a cache file created by the last CI run, I don't think that's a good plan at all. It will make it essentially impossible to build mathlib without the cache, and refactorings will become increasingly impossible as the original uncached tactics stop working.

simp only is a bit better since you can modify and fix it even if the original simp no longer works.

Scott Morrison (Oct 14 2022 at 00:54):

I had in mind something like this:

  • A tactic called cached_simp
  • If it is run without caching data present, it runs simp?, and stores the found lemmas in a persistent cache (maybe along with X.lean and X.olean we have X.cache).
  • If it is run with caching data present, it runs simp only [...] with the lemmas found in the cache.
  • There is an easy code action to replace the cached_simp with simp only [...], for debugging/fixing purposes.
  • Perhaps it also stores in the cache the form of the goal after the simp only [...] in the initial run, and if that isn't achieved by today's simp only [...], raise an error.
  • We can also run more intense CI occasionally that verifies that cached_simp would recreate its cached data.

It seems like that adds up to something functionally equivalent to our current simp only [...], except that the giant list of lemmas is stored out of the reader's sight.

Scott Morrison (Oct 14 2022 at 00:55):

In fact it does something a little better. Something that I really don't like at the moment is when I write simp? [X, Y], and it spits back simp only [A, B, C, D, X, E, F, G, Y, H]. This has lost the semantic intent that X and Y are additional to the usual simp set, and are meaningful here, while everything else is just cached data. (One could fix this with a version like `simp only [special_lemmas] [boring_lemmas], I guess.)

Scott Morrison (Nov 10 2022 at 06:06):

I'd be pretty surprised if my refactors are responsible for this gain. This is a single-threaded build, and in general while a dependency-reducing refactor will hopefully speed up multi-thread builds (by broadening the frontier of files that can be simultaneously compiled), such a refactor shouldn't really matter for single-threaded builds.

Scott Morrison (Nov 10 2022 at 06:07):

(In the case where you have lots of CPUs, at least.)

Junyan Xu (Nov 10 2022 at 06:39):

If you split a file into two parts and each part only has half of the original imports, then every simp (and probably every instance search) in the file will likely take only half of the original time, according to this earlier post. I think it may be illuminating to compare the following metric before and after the series of refactors: ∑ X : files, (LOC in X) * (LOC transitively imported by X).
